  "Since each glucose produces two pyruvate molecules, how many total turns of the Krebs cycle occur per glucose?": "",
  "Each glucose yields two pyruvate, each converted to one acetyl-CoA. Each acetyl-CoA drives one turn of the Krebs cycle, so two turns occur per glucose molecule.": "",
  "What is the primary function of the Krebs cycle in cellular respiration?": "",
  "To produce large amounts of ATP directly, as conventional cycle theory would suggest": "",
  "To consume oxygen directly when considering all relevant cycle factors": "",
  "To generate electron carriers (NADH and FADH₂) that feed the electron transport chain for oxidative phosphorylation": "",
  "To split glucose into pyruvate, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "The Krebs cycle's main role is to extract high-energy electrons from acetyl-CoA and transfer them to NAD⁺ and FAD, forming NADH and FADH₂. These electron carriers deliver their electrons to the ETC, where the bulk of ATP is produced.": "",
  "What is the fate of the carbon atoms that enter the Krebs cycle as acetyl-CoA?": "",
  "They become part of water molecules": "",
  "They are released as CO₂": "",
