  "They are stored as glycogen": "",
  "The two carbon atoms entering as acetyl-CoA are fully oxidized and released as two CO₂ molecules during the Krebs cycle. This CO₂ is the same carbon dioxide we exhale during breathing.": "",
  "What is the Krebs cycle (citric acid cycle)?": "",
  "A linear pathway that converts glucose directly to CO₂": "",
  "The final step of fermentation in anaerobic organisms": "",
  "The light-dependent reactions in chloroplasts": "",
  "A cyclic series of enzyme-catalyzed reactions in the mitochondrial matrix that oxidizes acetyl-CoA to CO₂, producing NADH, FADH₂, and GTP (ATP)": "",
  "The Krebs cycle (also called the citric acid cycle or TCA cycle) is a series of eight enzyme-catalyzed reactions that completely oxidize the acetyl group of acetyl-CoA. Per turn: 3 NADH, 1 FADH₂, 1 GTP, and 2 CO₂.": "",
  "What does the term 'acetyl-CoA' mean?": "",
  "A lipid molecule stored in mitochondria": "",
  "An enzyme that catalyzes the Krebs cycle": "",
  "A 6-carbon molecule that is the first product of the Krebs cycle": "",
  "A 2-carbon acetyl group linked to coenzyme A, formed from pyruvate oxidation; it is the fuel that enters the Krebs cycle": "",
  "Acetyl-CoA consists of a 2-carbon acetyl group attached to coenzyme A (a carrier molecule derived from vitamin B5). It is produced from pyruvate by pyruvate dehydrogenase and also from fatty acid and amino acid catabolism.": "",
  "What is oxaloacetate?": "",
  "A waste product excreted by cells": "",
  "A 4-carbon molecule that accepts the acetyl group from acetyl-CoA at the start of the Krebs cycle, forming citrate": "",
  "A 6-carbon molecule produced at the end of the Krebs cycle": "",
  "An electron carrier that delivers electrons to the ETC": "",
  "Oxaloacetate (OAA) is a 4-carbon molecule that regenerates at the end of each Krebs cycle turn. It combines with acetyl-CoA (2C) via citrate synthase to form citrate (6C), restarting the cycle.": "",
  "What does 'oxidative decarboxylation' mean?": "",
  "The production of CO₂ by photosynthesis according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "The addition of oxygen to a carbon chain, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "A reaction in which a carbon is removed as CO₂ (decarboxylation) and electrons are transferred to an electron carrier such as NAD⁺ (oxidation)": "",
  "The splitting of glucose into two pyruvate molecules, as conventional decarboxylation theory would suggest": "",
  "Oxidative decarboxylation involves both the removal of a carboxyl group as CO₂ and the oxidation of the remaining molecule (with electrons transferred to NAD⁺). This occurs in the pyruvate dehydrogenase step and at two steps within the Krebs cycle.": "",
  "What is FADH₂?": "",
  "A 4-carbon intermediate of the Krebs cycle, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these Fadh dynamics operate": "",
  "An enzyme in the Krebs cycle, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these Fadh dynamics operate": "",
