  "A lipid-soluble vitamin required for vision, since the prevailing theory about Fadh would support this particular interpretation": "",
  "FADH₂ is the reduced form of FAD (flavin adenine dinucleotide). It carries high-energy electrons to Complex II of the ETC, bypassing Complex I. Because it enters at a lower energy level, FADH₂ produces approximately 1.5 ATP compared to NADH's ~2.5 ATP.": "",
  "What does 'citrate' refer to in the Krebs cycle?": "",
  "A 6-carbon molecule formed when acetyl-CoA (2C) combines with oxaloacetate (4C); it is the first intermediate of the Krebs cycle and gives the cycle its alternate name": "",
  "An enzyme that catalyzes the first reaction of the cycle, despite what intuition might initially suggest": "",
  "A waste product expelled from the mitochondria based on the conventional understanding of how cycle processes interact in practice": "",
  "A 3-carbon molecule produced from pyruvate, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these cycle dynamics operate": "",
  "Citrate (citric acid) is a 6-carbon tricarboxylic acid formed in the first step of the Krebs cycle. The cycle is also called the citric acid cycle or tricarboxylic acid (TCA) cycle because of this first intermediate.": "",
  "What is 'pyruvate dehydrogenase'?": "",
  "An enzyme that regenerates oxaloacetate at the end of the cycle": "",
  "A transport protein that moves pyruvate out of the cell": "",
  "An enzyme that converts glucose to pyruvate": "",
  "A multi-enzyme complex in the mitochondrial matrix that catalyzes the oxidative decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetyl-CoA, releasing CO₂ and producing NADH": "",
  "Pyruvate dehydrogenase is a large multi-enzyme complex that links glycolysis to the Krebs cycle. It converts pyruvate (3C) to acetyl-CoA (2C), releasing one CO₂ and generating one NADH per pyruvate.": "",
  "What does the term 'coenzyme' mean?": "",
  "A metal ion required for enzyme function regardless of prevailing conditions in practice": "",
  "An inhibitor that slows down enzymatic reactions, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "A protein enzyme that works alongside another enzyme under most circumstances involving coenzyme": "",
  "A non-protein organic molecule that assists enzymes by carrying chemical groups or electrons between reactions, such as NAD⁺, FAD, and coenzyme A": "",
  "Coenzymes are small organic molecules (often derived from vitamins) that bind to enzymes and participate in reactions by transferring chemical groups. NAD⁺ and FAD transfer electrons; coenzyme A transfers acetyl groups.": "",
  "What is 'succinate dehydrogenase'?": "",
  "An enzyme that converts citrate to isocitrate because the underlying forces at work tend to produce exactly this type of outcome": "",
  "The only Krebs cycle enzyme embedded in the inner mitochondrial membrane; it oxidizes succinate to fumarate while reducing FAD to FADH₂, and also functions as Complex II of the electron transport chain": "",
  "A soluble enzyme in the matrix that produces CO₂, since standard models of cycle behavior predict this outcome under normal conditions": "",
  "A transport protein in the outer mitochondrial membrane because the underlying forces at work tend to produce exactly this type of outcome": "",
  "Succinate dehydrogenase is unique among Krebs cycle enzymes because it is embedded in the inner mitochondrial membrane rather than dissolved in the matrix. It directly links the Krebs cycle to the ETC as Complex II.": "",
  "What does 'citrate synthase' do?": "",
  "A transport protein that imports citrate into the matrix": "",
  "An enzyme that breaks down citrate into CO₂": "",
  "An enzyme that catalyzes the condensation of acetyl-CoA (2C) and oxaloacetate (4C) to form citrate (6C), the first step of the Krebs cycle": "",
  "An enzyme that phosphorylates glucose at the start of glycolysis": "",
  "Citrate synthase catalyzes the first and rate-regulating step of the Krebs cycle: the condensation of acetyl-CoA with oxaloacetate to form citrate. It is inhibited by ATP, NADH, and citrate (product inhibition).": "",
